---
import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

export const meta = {
  title: "AP Digital Portfolio: How to Submit Your Capstone or Art Project",
  description: "Stressing over how to upload your AP Capstone or Art project? Discover the exact steps, file limits, and deadlines to ensure your digital portfolio gets submitted on time.",
  category: "guide",
  published: "2026-03-15",
};

const schema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": ["Article", "FAQPage"],
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the AP Digital Portfolio?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The AP Digital Portfolio is an online platform created by the College Board that allows students to submit digital artifacts—like research papers, artwork, and code—for specific AP courses, such as AP Capstone, AP Art and Design, and AP Computer Science Principles."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I log in to the AP Digital Portfolio?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "You log in to the AP Digital Portfolio using your standard College Board account credentials. You must be enrolled in a supported AP class by your teacher or AP coordinator to access the submission portal."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is the deadline for submitting my AP Digital Portfolio?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The deadline varies slightly by year but is typically in late April or early May. You must submit your work before the final College Board deadline, and your teacher may set an earlier internal deadline."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What file types are supported in the AP Digital Portfolio?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Supported file types include PDF for documents, JPG/PNG for images, and MP4/MOV for video files. Always check the specific requirements for your course, as file size limits apply."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I edit my submission after uploading it to the AP Digital Portfolio?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, you can edit or replace your uploaded files at any time before you click 'Submit Final'. Once you submit the final version and your teacher approves it, you cannot make further changes."
      }
    }
  ],
  "headline": meta.title,
  "description": meta.description,
  "datePublished": meta.published
};
---

<SiteLayout site="westmount" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/ap-digital-portfolio" schema={JSON.stringify(schema)}>
  <div class="container page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>AP Digital Portfolio: A Complete Student Guide</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Navigate the College Board's submission portal for AP Capstone, Art, and Computer Science.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h2>Introduction: What is the AP Digital Portfolio?</h2>
      <p>Not every AP exam requires you to sit in a quiet room bubbling in Scantron circles for three hours. If you're enrolled in courses like AP Capstone (Seminar or Research), AP Art and Design, or AP Computer Science Principles, a significant portion of your final score is based on a project.</p>

      <p>The <strong>AP Digital Portfolio</strong> is the College Board's official online platform where you will upload and submit these long-term projects, research papers, artworks, and computer programs to be graded by AP readers.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>How to Access the Platform</h2>
      <p>To access the AP Digital Portfolio, you do not need a special link or new account. You simply log in using the same College Board account you used to register for your AP exams, view SAT scores, or access My AP.</p>

      <h3>The Setup Process:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Step 1: Get Your Join Code.</strong> Your teacher or AP coordinator will give you a "Join Code" at the beginning of the school year.</li>
        <li><strong>Step 2: Enroll in My AP.</strong> Enter this code into your College Board account to officially enroll in the class section.</li>
        <li><strong>Step 3: Access the Portfolio.</strong> Once enrolled in a supported class, the AP Digital Portfolio link will automatically appear in your account dashboard.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <h3>Key Concept: Teacher Review vs. College Board Submission</h3>
      <p>The submission process is typically a two-step verification:</p>
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Draft Submission:</strong> You upload your work. Your teacher can review it and check it for plagiarism using integrated tools like Turnitin.</li>
        <li><strong>Final Submission:</strong> You click "Submit Final." Once you confirm this step and the deadline passes, your work is locked and sent to the College Board for grading.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>File Requirements and Limits</h2>
      <p>One of the most common reasons students panic the night before the deadline is encountering file size or format errors. The AP Digital Portfolio is strict about what it accepts.</p>

      <h3>Accepted Formats by Course Type:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>AP Capstone (Research Papers):</strong> Only PDFs are accepted. Do not try to upload Microsoft Word (.docx) or Google Docs links. You must export your work to PDF first.</li>
        <li><strong>AP Art and Design (Images):</strong> High-resolution JPG or PNG files. Check your specific portfolio type (2D, 3D, or Drawing) for size limits.</li>
        <li><strong>AP Computer Science Principles (Video/Code):</strong> MP4, WMV, AVI, or MOV for your program video. PDFs for your written responses and program code.</li>
      </ul>

      <p><em>Warning:</em> Do not include your name anywhere in your files (unless specifically instructed). AP grading is blind, meaning graders should not know your identity.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Real-World Example: A Common Mistake</h2>
      <p>Consider an AP Computer Science student who creates an amazing, complex app. They record a 2-minute video demonstrating the app and try to upload it on deadline day. However, the College Board strictly limits the video to 1 minute and a specific file size (e.g., 30MB). The portal rejects the file, and the student misses the deadline while frantically trying to compress and edit the video.</p>
      <p><strong>The Lesson:</strong> Always check the file constraints at the start of your project, not the night it's due.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <h2>Why It Matters to You</h2>
      <h3>Your Score Depends On It</h3>
      <p>For courses like AP Research or AP Seminar, your uploaded portfolio constitutes a massive percentage of your final AP score (often 50% or more). Failing to submit your work correctly—or missing the final College Board deadline—means you will not receive a score for the course, regardless of how well you did on any end-of-year presentations.</p>

      <p>After conquering your high school academics and stepping into adulthood, shifting from grades to financial literacy is a critical transition. For those eager to build real-world wealth, checking out fundamentals like the <a href="/historical-average-annual-return-sp-500">historical average annual return of the S&P 500</a> or learning <a href="/marketwatch-sp-500">how to track market trends on MarketWatch</a> can set you up for long-term success.</p>

      <h3>Internal Deadlines</h3>
      <p>Your teacher will likely set an "internal deadline" that is days or weeks before the official College Board deadline. Respect this internal deadline. The platform often crashes or slows down significantly on the final day due to thousands of students trying to upload large files simultaneously across the country.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>What is the AP Digital Portfolio?</summary>
        <p>The AP Digital Portfolio is an online platform created by the College Board that allows students to submit digital artifacts—like research papers, artwork, and code—for specific AP courses, such as AP Capstone, AP Art and Design, and AP Computer Science Principles.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How do I log in to the AP Digital Portfolio?</summary>
        <p>You log in to the AP Digital Portfolio using your standard College Board account credentials. You must be enrolled in a supported AP class by your teacher or AP coordinator to access the submission portal.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What is the deadline for submitting my AP Digital Portfolio?</summary>
        <p>The deadline varies slightly by year but is typically in late April or early May. You must submit your work before the final College Board deadline, and your teacher may set an earlier internal deadline.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What file types are supported in the AP Digital Portfolio?</summary>
        <p>Supported file types include PDF for documents, JPG/PNG for images, and MP4/MOV for video files. Always check the specific requirements for your course, as file size limits apply.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Can I edit my submission after uploading it to the AP Digital Portfolio?</summary>
        <p>Yes, you can edit or replace your uploaded files at any time before you click 'Submit Final'. Once you submit the final version and your teacher approves it, you cannot make further changes.</p>
      </details>
    </section>
  </div>  <style is:inline>
    .page-content { max-width: 900px; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.5rem; }
    .hero { text-align: center; padding: 3rem 0 2rem; }
    .hero h1 { font-size: 2.2rem; font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 0.5rem; }
    .subtitle { color: var(--text-secondary); font-size: 1.1rem; }
    .card { background: var(--card-bg); border: 1px solid var(--border-color); border-radius: 12px; padding: 1.5rem; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    .callout { background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent-color) 10%, transparent); border-left: 4px solid var(--accent-color); padding: 1rem 1.5rem; border-radius: 0 8px 8px 0; margin: 1.5rem 0; }
    .faq-section details { margin: 1rem 0; padding: 1rem; background: var(--card-bg); border-radius: 8px; border: 1px solid var(--border-color); }
    .faq-section summary { font-weight: 600; cursor: pointer; }
  </style>
</SiteLayout>